ød","1272–Female":"1272–Afdød","1240–Male":"1240–Afdød","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","22 June 1240":"22. juni 1240","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"22 June 1240–":"22 juni 1240–Overleden","1272–Female":"1272–Overleden","1240–Male":"1240–Overleden","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","22 June 1240":"22 juni 1240","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"en":{"22 June 1240–":"22 June 1240–Deceased","1272–Female":"1272–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","22 June 1240":"22 June 1240","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lathom","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Latham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Latham","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lathom in Lancashire, or occasionally perhaps from Laytham in Yorkshire. The placenames mean ‘at the barns’, from <i>hlǫthum</i>, the dative plural form of Old Norse <i>hlatha</i> ‘barn, store house’."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Knt","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from the English county. This is probably named with a Celtic word meaning ‘border’. Use as a given name is of recent origin, but it is now quite popular. It may in part be seen as a short form of   Kenton ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names 